"(1) (i) The hum of the agricultural station’s ventilation system pulsed through the narrow corridor, a low, steady rhythm that had accompanied for years. He paused by the reinforced glass wall, watching the pale blue glow of the hydroponics bays through the early morning light that filtered through the dust-flecked panels overhead.\n(2) The air smelled faintly of ozone and nutrient mist, a scent that never quite changed, even after a century of progress. (ii) His gloved fingers tightened around the data tablet as an alert flashed on the station’s central monitor.\n(3) A red warning icon blinked insistently above the cryo-pod bay, its alphanumeric code scrolling: CRYO-12 INTEGRITY BREACH. Julian Ross.\n(4) Julian’s breath caught in his chest, a sharp, involuntary shiver that had nothing to do with the chilled air that seeped through the walls.\n(5) He knew the sound of that alarm all too well. Ross 128 Agricultural Station. witnessed a cryo-pod integrity breach.\n(6) (iii) He was the only one scheduled to check the cryo pods that morning, a routine that had become almost ritualistic.\n(7) The station’s quiet was broken only by the distant clatter of maintenance drones and the soft hiss of water being recycled.\n(8) Julian’s reflection warped in the glass as he stared at the alert, his eyes narrowing to slits against the rising panic. February 27, 2226.\n(9) (iv) The pod in question, number twelve, was supposed to be empty—its occupant in deep sleep cycles, monitored by the station’s neural net.\n(10) But the warning meant something"